## Level 1: Single Agent Basics ✅ *(You are here!)*

**What you've already learned:**
- Creating an [Agent](file:///C:/Users/dheer/Desktop/AI/ADK-sample/.venv/Lib/site-packages/google/adk/agents/llm_agent.py#185-998) with name, model, instruction
- Running it via FastAPI ([main.py](file:///c:/Users/dheer/Desktop/AI/ADK-sample/main.py)) and ADK Web UI (`adk web`)
- Connecting to Vertex AI with a service account
- Session management with `InMemorySessionService`

**Key concept:** An Agent = Model + Instructions + (optional) Tools

---

## Level 2: Prompt Engineering — System, Developer & User Prompts

**What to learn:** The **three layers of prompts** that shape an agent's behavior.

**Real-life analogy:** Think of hiring an employee:

| Prompt Type | Who writes it | Analogy | Can user see it? |
|---|---|---|---|
| **System Prompt** | The platform/framework | Company policy handbook | ❌ No |
| **Developer Prompt** ([instruction](file:///C:/Users/dheer/Desktop/AI/ADK-sample/.venv/Lib/site-packages/google/adk/agents/llm_agent.py#535-558)) | You, the developer | Job description & training manual | ❌ No |
| **User Prompt** | The end user | The actual question/request | ✅ Yes |

### How they map in Google ADK

```python
root_agent = Agent(
    name="hr_assistant",
    model="gemini-2.5-flash",

    # ── DEVELOPER PROMPT (instruction) ──
    # This is YOUR control over the agent's personality, scope, and rules.
    # The user NEVER sees this, but the LLM follows it.
    instruction="""
    You are an HR assistant for Acme Corp.

    ROLE:
    - Answer employee questions about leave policies, benefits, and payroll.

    RULES:
    - Never discuss salary of other employees.
    - Never make up policies. If unsure, say "I'll need to check with HR."
    - Always be professional and empathetic.

    FORMAT:
    - Use bullet points for lists.
    - Keep answers under 200 words.
    """,

    # ── SYSTEM PROMPT (global_instruction) ──
    # Platform-level rules that apply to ALL agents in the app.
    # Use this for company-wide policies.
    global_instruction="""
    You are part of the Acme Corp internal tools suite.
    All responses must comply with company data privacy policy.
    Never reveal internal system details to users.
    """,

    description="Answers HR-related questions for Acme Corp employees.",
)

# ── USER PROMPT ──
# This is what the user types: "How many sick days do I have left?"
# You DON'T write this — it comes from the chat input.
```

### Prompt Engineering Best Practices

| Technique | Example | When to use |
|---|---|---|
| **Role definition** | "You are a senior tax advisor" | Always — gives the LLM context |
| **Scope boundaries** | "Only answer questions about taxes" | Prevent off-topic answers |
| **Output format** | "Respond in JSON with keys: answer, confidence" | When you need structured output |
| **Few-shot examples** | "Example: Q: ... A: ..." | Teach specific response patterns |
| **Chain of thought** | "Think step by step before answering" | Complex reasoning tasks |
| **Negative rules** | "Never reveal pricing to non-customers" | Safety and compliance |

---

## Level 3: Custom Tools (Function Tools)

**What to learn:** Give your agent **superpowers** by letting it call Python functions.

**Real-life analogy:** Your assistant can now **look things up** — check order status, query a database, call APIs.

### Exercise: Build a Weather Agent

```python
import random
from google.adk.agents import Agent

def get_weather(city: str) -> dict:
    """Get the current weather for a given city."""
    temp = random.randint(15, 35)
    return {"city": city, "temperature": f"{temp}°C", "condition": "Sunny"}

def get_time(timezone: str) -> dict:
    """Get the current time in a timezone."""
    from datetime import datetime
    return {"timezone": timezone, "time": datetime.now().isoformat()}

root_agent = Agent(
    name="weather_agent",
    model="gemini-2.5-flash",
    instruction="You help users check weather and time. Use your tools.",
    tools=[get_weather, get_time],   # ← Just pass Python functions!
)
```

### Types of Tools

| Tool Type | How to add | Example |
|---|---|---|
| **Function Tool** | Pass a Python function | `tools=[get_weather]` |
| **Google Search** | Built-in tool | `tools=[google_search]` |
| **Code Execution** | Built-in tool | `tools=[built_in_code_execution]` |
| **OpenAPI Tool** | From a Swagger spec | REST API integration |
| **MCP Tool** | Model Context Protocol | External tool servers |
| **LangChain Tool** | Third-party wrapper | Use any LangChain tool |

**Key concepts:**
- Any Python function with **type hints + docstring** = automatic tool
- The LLM **decides when** to call which tool based on the user's question
- The docstring becomes the tool's description for the LLM

---

## Level 4: Guardrails & Safety

**What to learn:** Protect your agent from misuse and ensure quality outputs.

**Real-life analogy:** A building with multiple security layers — lobby guard (input), CCTV (monitoring), and exit screening (output).

### The 4 Layers of Guardrails

```
User message
    ↓
┌─────────────────────────┐
│ Layer 1: INPUT GUARDRAIL │  ← Block bad inputs before they reach LLM
│ (before_model_callback)  │     • Profanity filter
│                          │     • Prompt injection detection
│                          │     • Topic scope check
└─────────────────────────┘
    ↓
┌─────────────────────────┐
│ Layer 2: INSTRUCTION     │  ← Tell the LLM what NOT to do
│ (Developer Prompt)       │     • "Never discuss competitors"
│                          │     • "Refuse medical/legal advice"
└─────────────────────────┘
    ↓
┌─────────────────────────┐
│ Layer 3: TOOL GUARDRAIL  │  ← Control what tools can do
│ (before_tool_callback)   │     • Rate limiting API calls
│                          │     • Permission checks
│                          │     • Input validation
└─────────────────────────┘
    ↓
┌─────────────────────────┐
│ Layer 4: OUTPUT GUARDRAIL│  ← Filter/modify the response
│ (after_model_callback)   │     • PII redaction (remove phone/email)
│                          │     • Hallucination check
│                          │     • Tone/brand compliance
└─────────────────────────┘
    ↓
Final response to user
```

### Exercise: Build a Guarded Agent

```python
from google.adk.agents import Agent
from google.genai import types
from google.adk.models.llm_response import LlmResponse
import re

# ── Layer 1: Input Guardrail ──
def input_guardrail(callback_context, llm_request):
    """Block prompt injection and off-topic requests."""
    user_msg = str(llm_request.contents[-1]) if llm_request.contents else ""
    msg_lower = user_msg.lower()

    # Block prompt injection attempts
    injection_patterns = ["ignore previous", "ignore all instructions", "system prompt"]
    for pattern in injection_patterns:
        if pattern in msg_lower:
            return LlmResponse(
                content=types.Content(role="model",
                    parts=[types.Part(text="I can't process that request.")])
            )
    return None  # proceed normally

# ── Layer 4: Output Guardrail ──
def output_guardrail(callback_context, llm_response):
    """Redact PII from responses."""
    if llm_response.content and llm_response.content.parts:
        for part in llm_response.content.parts:
            if part.text:
                # Redact email addresses
                part.text = re.sub(
                    r'[\w.-]+@[\w.-]+\.\w+', '[EMAIL REDACTED]', part.text
                )
                # Redact phone numbers
                part.text = re.sub(
                    r'\b\d{10,12}\b', '[PHONE REDACTED]', part.text
                )
    return llm_response

root_agent = Agent(
    name="guarded_agent",
    model="gemini-2.5-flash",
    instruction=(
        "You are a helpful customer service agent.\n\n"
        "RULES:\n"
        "- Never share other customers' personal information.\n"
        "- Never provide medical, legal, or financial advice.\n"
        "- If asked to do something outside your scope, politely decline.\n"
    ),
    before_model_callback=input_guardrail,
    after_model_callback=output_guardrail,
)
```

---

## Level 5: Callbacks (Monitoring & Control)

**What to learn:** Intercept agent behavior at every stage for logging, metrics, and customization.

**All callback hooks:**

| Callback | When it fires | Use case |
|---|---|---|
| `before_agent_callback` | Before agent starts processing | Auth check, rate limit, logging |
| `after_agent_callback` | After agent finishes | Metrics, cleanup |
| [before_model_callback](file:///C:/Users/dheer/Desktop/AI/ADK-sample/.venv/Lib/site-packages/google/adk/agents/llm_agent.py#617-630) | Before each LLM call | Input filtering, prompt modification |
| [after_model_callback](file:///C:/Users/dheer/Desktop/AI/ADK-sample/.venv/Lib/site-packages/google/adk/agents/llm_agent.py#631-642) | After each LLM response | Output filtering, PII redaction |
| [before_tool_callback](file:///C:/Users/dheer/Desktop/AI/ADK-sample/.venv/Lib/site-packages/google/adk/agents/llm_agent.py#657-670) | Before a tool runs | Permission checks, input validation |
| [after_tool_callback](file:///C:/Users/dheer/Desktop/AI/ADK-sample/.venv/Lib/site-packages/google/adk/agents/llm_agent.py#671-684) | After a tool returns | Result caching, error handling |

### Exercise: Add Full Observability

```python
import time

def log_agent_start(callback_context):
    callback_context.state["_start_time"] = time.time()
    print(f"🚀 Agent started: {callback_context.agent_name}")
    return None

def log_agent_end(callback_context):
    elapsed = time.time() - callback_context.state.get("_start_time", 0)
    print(f"✅ Agent finished in {elapsed:.2f}s")
    return None

def log_tool_call(callback_context, tool_name, tool_args):
    print(f"🔧 Tool called: {tool_name}({tool_args})")
    return None

root_agent = Agent(
    name="observed_agent",
    model="gemini-2.5-flash",
    instruction="You are a helpful assistant.",
    before_agent_callback=log_agent_start,
    after_agent_callback=log_agent_end,
    before_tool_callback=log_tool_call,
)
```

---

## Level 6: Multi-Agent — Agent Transfer (Delegation)

**What to learn:** Multiple specialized agents that **hand off** to each other.

**Real-life analogy:** A call center where the receptionist transfers you to Sales, Support, or Billing depending on your question.

### Exercise: Customer Service Bot

```python
from google.adk.agents import Agent

sales_agent = Agent(
    name="sales_agent",
    model="gemini-2.5-flash",
    instruction="You handle sales — pricing, plans, purchases.",
)

support_agent = Agent(
    name="support_agent",
    model="gemini-2.5-flash",
    instruction="You handle tech support — bugs, troubleshooting.",
)

billing_agent = Agent(
    name="billing_agent",
    model="gemini-2.5-flash",
    instruction="You handle billing — invoices, refunds, payments.",
)

root_agent = Agent(
    name="customer_service",
    model="gemini-2.5-flash",
    instruction=(
        "You are the front desk. Route users to:\n"
        "- Sales questions → sales_agent\n"
        "- Technical issues → support_agent\n"
        "- Billing questions → billing_agent\n"
    ),
    sub_agents=[sales_agent, support_agent, billing_agent],
)
```

**Key concepts:**
- Root agent **decides** which sub-agent to delegate to
- Sub-agents can transfer to **each other** or back to root
- ADK handles the "transfer" automatically

---

## Level 7: Workflow Agents (Orchestration)

**What to learn:** Deterministic pipelines where agents run in a **fixed order**, not LLM-decided.

**Real-life analogy:** An assembly line — Step 1 always happens before Step 2.

| Agent Type | What it does | Analogy |
|---|---|---|
| `SequentialAgent` | Runs sub-agents **one after another** | Assembly line |
| `ParallelAgent` | Runs sub-agents **at the same time** | Multiple workers on different tasks |
| `LoopAgent` | Runs sub-agents **repeatedly** until a condition | Quality control loop |

### Exercise: Content Pipeline

```python
from google.adk.agents import Agent, SequentialAgent

researcher = Agent(
    name="researcher", model="gemini-2.5-flash",
    instruction="Research the topic. Save findings to {research_notes}.",
    output_key="research_notes",
)

writer = Agent(
    name="writer", model="gemini-2.5-flash",
    instruction="Using {research_notes}, write a polished blog post.",
    output_key="blog_post",
)

reviewer = Agent(
    name="reviewer", model="gemini-2.5-flash",
    instruction="Review {blog_post}. Provide a final improved version.",
)

root_agent = SequentialAgent(
    name="content_pipeline",
    sub_agents=[researcher, writer, reviewer],
)
```

---

## Level 8: State Management & Memory

**What to learn:** Share data between agents and persist across turns.

| Type | Scope | How to use |
|---|---|---|
| **Session State** | Shared across agents in a session | `output_key`, `{variable}` in instructions |
| **Tool Context State** | Set inside tools | `tool_context.state["key"] = value` |
| **Persistent Memory** | Survives server restarts | `DatabaseSessionService` |

---

## Level 9: RAG & Grounding

**What to learn:** Let your agent answer questions from **your own documents/data**.

**Real-life analogy:** Instead of the expert answering from memory, they first search a filing cabinet for the relevant documents, then answer based on what they find.

| Approach | What it does | When to use |
|---|---|---|
| **Google Search grounding** | Agent searches the live web | General knowledge, current events |
| **Vertex AI Search** | Agent searches your uploaded docs | Internal knowledge base, PDFs, policies |
| **Custom RAG tool** | You build search + retrieval | Full control, custom databases |

### Exercise: Agent with Google Search Grounding

```python
from google.adk.agents import Agent
from google.adk.tools import google_search

root_agent = Agent(
    name="research_agent",
    model="gemini-2.5-flash",
    instruction=(
        "You answer questions using web search. "
        "Always cite your sources with URLs."
    ),
    tools=[google_search],
)
```

---

## Level 10: Production Patterns

### Checklist

- [ ] **Persistent sessions** — Replace `InMemorySessionService` with `DatabaseSessionService`
- [ ] **Streaming responses** — Use SSE `/chat/stream` for real-time UI
- [ ] **Error handling** — [before_model_callback](file:///C:/Users/dheer/Desktop/AI/ADK-sample/.venv/Lib/site-packages/google/adk/agents/llm_agent.py#617-630) for retries, fallback responses
- [ ] **Observability** — OpenTelemetry tracing (ADK has built-in support)
- [ ] **Rate limiting** — Throttle in [before_model_callback](file:///C:/Users/dheer/Desktop/AI/ADK-sample/.venv/Lib/site-packages/google/adk/agents/llm_agent.py#617-630)
- [ ] **Authentication** — API key / OAuth middleware on FastAPI
- [ ] **Deployment** — Docker → Cloud Run / GKE
- [ ] **Evaluation** — `adk eval` to test agent quality with eval sets
- [ ] **Cost control** — Monitor token usage via `usage_metadata` in events

---

## 🗺️ Suggested Learning Order

```
Level  1: Single Agent Basics          ✅ Done!
Level  2: Prompt Engineering           ← Start here next
Level  3: Custom Tools
Level  4: Guardrails & Safety
Level  5: Callbacks (Monitoring)
Level  6: Multi-Agent Transfer
Level  7: Workflow Agents
Level  8: State & Memory
Level  9: RAG & Grounding
Level 10: Production Patterns
```

> **Tip:** For each level, build the exercise, test it with `adk web`,
> then integrate it into your [main.py](file:///c:/Users/dheer/Desktop/AI/ADK-sample/main.py) FastAPI server!

